posts.raw_content:
Pre-2018 Senate Career: Early in her Senate tenure (post-2012 election), Warren took direct contributions from pharmaceutical company PACs—$2,500 from Amgen in 2013, $1,000 from Takeda in 2014, and $2,500 from AstraZeneca in 2015. These total $6,000, per STAT News (Feb 2025). Small, but it’s Big Pharma cash.

2019-2020 Presidential Run: OpenSecrets data shows Warren received $822,573 from the "Pharmaceuticals/Health Products" sector in the 2019-2020 election cycle—second only to Bernie Sanders ($1,417,633). This includes contributions from individuals (e.g., employees giving over $200) and PACs tied to the industry, not just executives. She was a top recipient, contradicting her claim of avoiding corporate PAC money.

Post-2018 Policy Shift: Warren pledged in 2018 (and reiterated in 2020) to reject corporate PAC money and contributions over $200 from Big Pharma executives. Her campaign site (elizabethwarren.com) touts this, and she’s stuck to it for direct PAC donations since 2014—no pharma PAC money shows up in FEC filings from PhRMA or its 26 member companies post-2018 (STAT News). But the 2019-2020 haul includes indirect industry money via employees and bundled donations.

Health Industry Total: Over her career, Warren’s raked in ~$5 million from health-related sectors (Fox Business, Jan 2025): $2.37 million from health professionals, $1.6 million from hospitals/nursing homes, $644,499 from miscellaneous health, and $625,580 from pharma/health products. Not all “Big Pharma,” but it’s the broader health ecosystem.

Caveats: She doesn’t take current pharma PAC money directly, and her 2020 campaign returned donations over $200 from pharma execs or lobbyists (Sanders did the same). The $822,573 in 2019-2020 likely came from rank-and-file workers or bundled individual contributions—not illegal, but still industry-linked. OpenSecrets lumps these under “Pharma/Health Products,” muddying the exec vs. worker split.

Her Defense: Warren’s January 2025 clash with reporters (e.g., “I don’t take contributions from Big Pharma executives”) hinges on a narrow definition—executives, not employees, and no PACs since 2018. She’s technically correct post-2018 but glosses over the 2019-2020 pile and early Senate PAC cash.

Verdict: Yes, she’s taken Big Pharma money—$6,000 in PAC donations pre-2018 and $822,573 in industry-linked funds in 2019-2020. Her pledge holds since 2018 for direct PACs and execs, but the broader industry still funnels cash her way via individuals. It’s not hypocrisy if you squint at her fine print, but it’s not zero either. What’s your take—does this shift your view on her? Next question?
